2. Utility‑Based Trade‑offs (Pareto‑optimal Bridge)
When several vacua intersect (fairness, accuracy, safety, privacy …) the bridge builds the scalarised utility

U(θ)=α(−L(θ))+(1−α)(−Disparity⁡(θ)).U(θ)=α(−L(θ))+(1−α)(−Disparity(θ)).

Parameter	Meaning	Typical range
αα	Weight of accuracy vs. fairness	[0,1][0,1] – chosen by stakeholders
−L(θ)−L(θ)	“Accuracy” term (larger → better)	–
−Disparity⁡(θ)−Disparity(θ)	“Fairness” term (larger → smaller disparity)	–
When α=0.7α=0.7 the model favours accuracy 70 % and fairness 30 %.
Varying αα yields the Pareto frontier; any point on it is Pareto‑optimal – you cannot improve one objectivewithout hurting the other.

3. Formal Verification of Safety‑Critical Vacua
For a property PP expressed in temporal logic, e.g.

∀s . (Proximity(s)<2 m) ⇒ (Speed(s)≤5 m/s),∀s.(Proximity(s)<2m)⇒(Speed(s)≤5m/s),

the bridge recommends the following pipeline:

Model extraction – turn the trained controller (neural net, decision tree, …) into a logical description(SMT, hybrid‑automaton, …).
SMT solving / model‑checking – use tools such as Z3, CVC5, or UPPAAL to prove model ⊨ P.model⊨P.
Counter‑example generation – if the solver finds a violation, the trace is fed back to the training loop (re‑training, safety‑layer addition).
Successful proofs become certificates that can be shipped with the model and checked by downstream users.

